The play’s conclusion is revealed by the Witches early in Act One, albeit in the form of ambiguous prophecies. This
foreshadowing emphasises the inevitability of fate. Macbeth only acknowledges this in Act 5, when he says life is “full of
sound and fury, / Signifying nothing”, implying that his attempts to defy fate have been nothing more than ineffectual noise.
